In Linux, a superuser is the administrator (often called root), who has full control of the system.

Superuser can:

Install or remove software

Manage users and permissions

Configure the system

Access any file, even if permissions deny normal users

ðŸ”‘ Commands:

sudo â†’ Run a command as superuser (temporarily).
Example:

bash
Copy
Edit
sudo apt update
sudo apt install nano
su â†’ Switch to the superuser account.

ðŸ“¦ Software management:

Most Linux distros use package managers to install, update, or remove software.

Debian/Ubuntu: apt or apt-get

Fedora/RHEL/CentOS: dnf or yum

Example (Ubuntu/Debian):

bash
Copy
Edit
sudo apt update      # update package lists
sudo apt install vim # install vim editor
sudo apt remove vim  # remove vim
11. Shell Variables and Aliases
Shell Variables:
Variables store data (like numbers, strings, paths) in the shell.
Example:

bash
Copy
Edit
NAME="Zeeshan"
echo $NAME
Output â†’ Zeeshan

Some variables are environment variables, e.g.:

$HOME â†’ your home directory

$PATH â†’ list of directories where commands are searched

Aliases:
Aliases let you create shortcuts for long commands.
Example:

bash
Copy
Edit
alias ll='ls -la'
Now typing ll will run ls -la.

To remove an alias:

bash
Copy
Edit
unalias ll
ðŸ‘‰ Aliases save time, variables help store and reuse values
